  "concept": "Two survival skills here, and both show up in the DELF oral: spelling out loud, and giving your personal details.\n\nThe French alphabet has the same 26 letters as English, but the letter NAMES are pronounced differently — use the audio to hear them. What matters first is the question that triggers spelling: « Comment ça s'écrit ? » (How is it spelled?), and the verb épeler (to spell).\n\nFrench also writes accents on letters, and they are NOT optional decoration — they change pronunciation and sometimes meaning. Learn their names so you can spell aloud:\n  é = e accent aigu, è = e accent grave, ê = e accent circonflexe, ç = c cédille, ë = e tréma.\nSo « café » is spelled C-A-F-E accent aigu.\n\nTo ASK for information, French uses the question word quel / quelle (\"which / what\"). It behaves like an adjective, so it agrees with the noun: « Quel est votre nom ? » (nom is masculine → quel) but « Quelle est votre adresse ? » (adresse is feminine → quelle).\n\nThe details you'll give and ask for: le nom (surname), le prénom (first name), le numéro de téléphone (phone number), l'adresse, l'e-mail.\n\nA typical exchange: « — Quel est votre prénom ? — Léa. — Comment ça s'écrit ? — L, E accent aigu, A. »\n\nPractise spelling your own name out loud, including any accents — it's the single most likely thing you'll be asked to do in a real French conversation.",
